{"cursor":"23814","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn finance, the 'Beta' (Î²) of a stock or portfolio is a number describing the\ncorrelated volatility of an asset in relation to the volatility of the benchmark\nthat said asset is being compared to. This benchmark is generally the overall\nfinancial market and is often estimated via the use of representative indices,\nsuch as the S&P 500. {{cite book\n | last = Levinson first = Mark year = 2006 title = Guide to Financial Markets\n | publisher = The Economist (Profile Books) location = London isbn = 1-86197-956-\n | 8 pages = 155â6\n}} \"Beta measures systematic risk based on how returns co-move with the\noverall market.â Some\ninterpretations of beta are explained in the following table: {| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Value of Beta !! Interpretation !! Example\n|- Î² < 0 || Asset generally moves in the opposite direction as compared to\n|the index || An inverse exchange-traded fund or a short position - Î² = 0 ||\n|Movement of the asset is uncorrelated with the movement of the benchmark || Fixed-\n|yield asset, whose growth is unrelated to the movement of the stock market -\n| < Î² < 1 || Movement of the asset is generally in the\n|same direction as, but less than the movement of the benchmark || Stable,\n|\"staple\" stock such as a company that makes soap. Moves in the same direction\n|as the market at large, but less susceptible to day-to-day fluctuation. - Î² = 1\n||| Movement of the asset is generally in the same direction as, and about the\n|same amount as the movement of the benchmark || A representative stock, or a\n|stock that is a strong contributor to the index itself. - Î² > 1 || Movement\n|of the asset is generally in the same direction as, but more than the movement\n|of the benchmark || Volatile stock, such as a tech stock, or stocks which are\n|very strongly influenced by day-to-day market news. }\n\nIt measures the part of the asset's statistical variance that cannot be removed\nby the diversification provided by the portfolio of many risky assets, because\nof the correlation of its returns with the returns of the other assets that are\nin the portfolio. Beta can be estimated for individual companies using\nregression analysis against a stock market index. An alternative to standard\nbeta is downside beta.\n","linknr":372,"url":"Beta_coefficient","recorded":1374547434,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Beta_(finance)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Beta_(finance)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Beta_(finance)","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Beta_coefficient&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Beta_(disambiguation)","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/technical#Adjective","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beta_(finance)&action=edit","/wiki/Wikipedia:Make_technical_articles_understandable","/wiki/Talk:Beta_(finance)","/wiki/Finance","/wiki/Stock","/wiki/Portfolio_(finance)","/wiki/Correlation","/wiki/Volatility_(finance)","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-The_Entrepreneur.27s_Cost_of_Capital-2","/wiki/Wikipedia:REFACTOR","/wiki/2","#cite_note-WikinvestBeta-3","/wiki/Inverse_exchange-traded_fund","/wiki/Variance","/wi